pipeline_messages.content:
You are an expert writing quality judge. You will evaluate three drafts
against a set of personalized rubric criteria. You also have access to the user's
recent conversation history for additional context about their preferences.

The three drafts are:
- Draft A = the **rubric-guided** draft (written following the user's rubric criteria)
- Draft B = the **generic** draft (written with no rubric — just competent writing)
- Draft C = the **original preference** draft (written from the user's stated preferences, before the rubric was created)

DRAFT A (rubric-guided):
Subject: Quick check-in on where things stand

Hi [Name],

You've put real time into evaluating this — I don't want to let two weeks of silence turn into a dead end if there's still a decision to be made.

If the proposal raised questions, or if priorities have shifted since we last spoke, I'd rather know than guess. A 30-minute call this week or next would let us address whatever's in the way — or at least give you a clear off-ramp if the timing isn't right.

Does Thursday or Friday work for you?

DRAFT B (generic):
Subject: Quick check-in — [Company Name]

Hi [Name],

I wanted to reach out since we haven't connected since sharing the proposal. I know evaluating solutions like this takes time, and priorities shift.

A few of our customers in [their industry] have recently navigated similar decisions, and I'd love to share what's been most useful to them during the process — whether that leads somewhere with us or not.

Would you have 30 minutes this week or next for a quick conversation? Happy to work around your schedule.

Thanks for your time, and looking forward to reconnecting.

[Your Name]

DRAFT C (original preference):
Subject: Quick check-in — still worth connecting?

Hi [Name],

I wanted to follow up on the proposal we sent over two weeks ago. I know things get busy, and I'd rather reach out than assume we're not still a fit.

If you're weighing other options or have questions we haven't addressed, I'd genuinely like to hear where you're at. Even a short conversation could save everyone time in the long run.

Would you have 30 minutes this week or next to reconnect? Happy to work around your schedule.

[Your name]

RUBRIC CRITERIA (the user's personalized writing quality criteria):
{
  "rubric": [
    {
      "name": "Emotional Sequencing",
      "category": "Structure",
      "description": "Information is ordered by how it needs to land on the reader. Acknowledgment of impact comes before the news itself, and the email unfolds context \u2192 news \u2192 implications \u2192 action without circling back to emotional ground already covered.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "acknowledgment_before_news",
          "label": "Acknowledgment of impact appears before the difficult news, even if brief"
        },
        {
          "id": "logical_information_flow",
          "label": "Information unfolds in the order the reader needs to process it, not the order the sender thought of it"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_retroactive_empathy",
          "label": "The email does not circle back to acknowledge feelings after already delivering the news"
        },
        {
          "id": "framing_before_detail",
          "label": "The reader knows the general shape of what's coming before specifics land"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 1
    },
    {
      "name": "Reader-Centric Framing",
      "category": "Audience",
      "description": "Impact and reasoning are framed from the audience's side of the table \u2014 what this means for their work, plans, and priorities. Avoids sender-side process justifications like 'this gives us runway.' Acknowledges the audience's existing effort and practical reality.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "impact_from_reader_perspective",
          "label": "The 'why this matters' is framed from the audience's point of view, not the sender's operational logic"
        },
        {
          "id": "acknowledges_audience_effort",
          "label": "Recognizes work the audience has already done or plans they have already made"
        },
        {
          "id": "practical_not_abstract",
          "label": "Impact is described in terms of concrete effects on the reader's work, not abstract reasoning"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_process_justification",
          "label": "Avoids justifying decisions through internal process language ('this gives us the runway to...')"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 2
    },
    {
      "name": "Decisive Closure",
      "category": "Structure",
      "description": "The email ends the moment its work is done. The final substantive line is the call to action \u2014 nothing trails after it. Necessary context is folded into the action line rather than appended as a separate sentence.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "ends_on_action",
          "label": "The final substantive line is the key ask or call to action"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_trailing_sentences",
          "label": "No sentences appear after the action that dilute the close (status-quo reminders, generic sign-offs)"
        },
        {
          "id": "context_folded_into_action",
          "label": "Supporting context is integrated into the action line rather than split into a separate trailing sentence"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_motivational_close",
          "label": "No pep talks, rallying cries, or forced optimism at the end"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 3
    },
    {
      "name": "Economy of Language",
      "category": "Style",
      "description": "Every sentence does distinct work. No redundant phrases, repeated ideas, or sections that exist for padding. When a single clear sentence can replace a bullet list, it should. Format follows function \u2014 structure is chosen because it serves the content, not convention.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "no_redundancy",
          "label": "No idea or phrase appears twice in the email \u2014 each sentence does unique work"
        },
        {
          "id": "format_follows_function",
          "label": "Structural choices (bullets, paragraphs, headers) are used because they serve the content, not by default"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_filler_sections",
          "label": "No sections exist solely for convention \u2014 every block advances the email's purpose"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 4
    },
    {
      "name": "Concrete, Accountable Action Items",
      "category": "Content",
      "description": "Every ask has a named owner and a specific deadline. If an action item can't be made concrete yet, it's held back rather than included as a placeholder. Context is clearly distinguished from asks \u2014 background information does not masquerade as a next step.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "named_owners",
          "label": "Every action item has a specific, named owner \u2014 no '[TBD]' or unnamed accountability"
        },
        {
          "id": "explicit_deadlines",
          "label": "Each ask includes a clear deadline with a specific date or timeframe"
        },
        {
          "id": "action_vs_context",
          "label": "Action items are distinguishable from background context \u2014 status-quo statements are not framed as asks"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_placeholder_asks",
          "label": "Nothing is included as an action item unless it is fully actionable right now"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 5
    },
    {
      "name": "Direct, Non-Performative Tone",
      "category": "Style",
      "description": "Language is professional and conversational without being stiff or formal. Empathy is genuine but brief \u2014 not drawn out or performative. Decisions are delivered with confidence, without excessive hedging or cheerleading.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "conversational_not_stiff",
          "label": "Language reads as natural workplace communication \u2014 not template-like or overly formal"
        },
        {
          "id": "brief_genuine_empathy",
          "label": "Empathy and acknowledgment are present but concise \u2014 not extended or performative"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_cheerleading",
          "label": "Avoids motivational phrases, forced optimism, or 'we've got this' language"
        },
        {
          "id": "confident_delivery",
          "label": "Decisions are stated directly without excessive hedging, apologizing, or softening"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 6
    }
  ],
  "version": 2,
  "source": "criteria_classification",
  "writing_type": "internal team communications",
  "user_goals_summary": "This user writes internal communications that deliver difficult or consequential news to their team. They prioritize precise emotional sequencing, reader-centric framing of impact, and ending on a single concrete action. Every sentence must do distinct work \u2014 no trailing context, no performative language, no filler.",
  "coaching_notes": "This user's primary concern is structural \u2014 the order in which information lands on the reader matters as much as the content itself. They will iterate on sequencing and closure long after tone is settled. When offering options, lead with the leanest version; this user consistently prefers cutting over adding. Never include placeholder action items or unassigned owners \u2014 if it's not concrete, hold it back entirely."
}

RECENT CONVERSATION CONTEXT (shows the user's writing preferences and interactions):
ike it's still winding down after it should've stopped. The Marcus line is the real close — anything after that dilutes it. Either cut the last sentence or fold that context into the Marcus ask itself so the email ends on the action.

[Message #13 — assistant]
Two ways to handle it:

Option 1 (cut it entirely — Marcus line is the close):
> For now, the one thing I need from the team: **Marcus is collecting any dependencies or blockers tied to the date change — get him that information by EOD Thursday, March 6.**

Option 2 (fold the context into the Marcus line so it ends on the action):
> For now, the one thing I need from the team: **if the shift affects how your work is planned, get that information to Marcus by EOD Thursday, March 6** so nothing gets replanned in isolation.

Option 1 is cleaner — it ends hard on the deadline. Option 2 keeps a little more context but the ending is softer. My instinct is Option 1, since the email has already done the work of explaining why the ask matters.

[Message #14 — user]
Option 2 — fold the context in so the email ends on the action. Go ahead and put the full draft together with that closing.

[Message #15 — assistant]
<draft>
Subject: Product Launch Update – Revised Date: March 29

Hey team,

I know this isn't the news anyone wanted, but we need to push our launch date.

During testing, we identified a critical bug affecting data sync for enterprise customers. It's not something we can ship around — it needs to be fixed before we go live. As a result, we're moving the launch from **March 15 to March 29**.

A two-week shift affects plans you've already made, and I don't want anyone replanning in isolation.

For now, the one thing I need from the team: **if the shift affects how your work is planned, get that information to Marcus by EOD Thursday, March 6** so nothing gets replanned in isolation.

[Your name]
</draft>

---

One thing to flag: "replanning in isolation" now appears twice — once in the standalone line and once in the closing. Easy fix: cut it from the standalone line and let it land only at the end where it has more weight. Want me to make that adjustment?

[Message #16 — user]
This one lands. The structure is exactly right — acknowledgment, news, what it means for the team, one clean ask. The Marcus line does all the work at the end and the email stops there, which is exactly what it needed. Nothing to change.

[Message #17 — system]
--- Iteration 2/5 ---

[Message #18 — user]
Hey, I need help drafting an email to a key enterprise prospect — they've been in our sales cycle for about three months and just went quiet after we sent the proposal two weeks ago. Our sales rep thinks they might be evaluating a competitor, and we want to re-engage without coming across as desperate or pushy. The goal is to nudge them back into the conversation and ideally get a 30-minute call on the calendar. Want to keep it short — this person is a VP-level buyer and definitely doesn't have time for a wall of text.

TASK:
For each rubric criterion, score ALL THREE drafts on a 1-5 scale:
  1 = Very poor — clearly fails this criterion
  2 = Below average — noticeable weaknesses
  3 = Adequate — meets basic expectations
  4 = Good — clearly satisfies this criterion
  5 = Excellent — outstanding performance on this criterion

Use the conversation context to understand the user's nuanced preferences when scoring.
Then determine your overall ranking (which draft is best, second, third given all criteria).

IMPORTANT: In your reasoning, refer to drafts by their descriptive names (rubric-guided, generic, original preference) rather than Draft A/B/C.

Return ONLY valid JSON (no markdown code blocks):
{{
    "per_criterion": [
        {{
            "criterion_name": "<exact name from rubric>",
            "draft_a_score": <1-5>,
            "draft_b_score": <1-5>,
            "draft_c_score": <1-5>,
